Genus 
<taxonomicName id="BA526585682B6BE3777EE957A2DE948D" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:2509" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Polyergus" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Polyergus Latreille" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Polyergus Latreille</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="8F5B437324E6C4923F47C929EF2D1EDE" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="A1DFCF710C77FEDCFC156CB6A8E5F8D9" pageNumber="30">
The members of this genus are obligate slave-raiders of other ants, mostly species in the 
<taxonomicName id="BCDA1D8E6A84E7001ADCF8ACEC88E24D" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:29086" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Formica" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Formica fusca Linnaeus" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fusca">Formica fusca-group</taxonomicName>
. The California populations of 
<taxonomicName id="6A10969F110FC32FF91D123BB79CC9CE" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:2509" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Polyergus" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Polyergus Latreille" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Polyergus</taxonomicName>
are here treated as a single variable species, 
<taxonomicName id="84DD8EA9489B5A2A166F8085709F4C76" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:34388" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Polyergus" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Polyergus breviceps Emery" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="breviceps">P. breviceps Emery</taxonomicName>
. This implies synonymy of 
<taxonomicName id="6EB78F9258352E74F82946CF9F69F6B5" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:239385" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Polyergus" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Polyergus laeviceps" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="laeviceps">P. laeviceps Wheeler</taxonomicName>
(type locality: Mt. Tamalpais, California) under 
<taxonomicName id="9647F115666916FA9032F076B6E78F1E" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:34388" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Polyergus" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Polyergus breviceps Emery" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="breviceps">P. breviceps</taxonomicName>
but no formal change is proposed here because the entire complex needs comprehensive taxonomic evaluation. Within California there is considerable interregional variation in worker morphology and biology (including the host species attacked), but I have seen no evidence of more than one species occurring in any given locality. One might expect there to be pronounced interpopulation variation in 
<taxonomicName id="422B96FEB4109E4637F607AC1147F43B" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:34388" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Polyergus" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Polyergus breviceps Emery" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="breviceps">P. breviceps</taxonomicName>
because of the limited dispersal of the queens (Topoff 1999). References (partial list): Agosti (1994b), Creighton (1950a), Greenberg et al. (2004), Hasegawa et al. (2002), 
<normalizedToken id="D061EEA37207D1349080EFF77F7C5667" originalValue="HÃ¶lldobler">Hoelldobler</normalizedToken>
(1985), Topoff (1990, 1999), Wheeler (1968).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
